##Another official in Iran has died, setting up a "Vulcan Mountain"

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Yu Xiaoxuan, reporter, thepaper.cn

Overseas network

Iran's state television, citing the President of the Bundestag, said 23 members of parliament have been diagnosed with the new coronavirus, Al Arabiya News reported on March 3.

The head of Iran's emergency health service, Pir Hossein Kolivand, has been infected with the new coronavirus, Al Arabiya reported. Iranian media report that an adviser to the country's justice minister has died from a new coronavirus infection.

According to the latest news from the Iranian Ministry of Health, on March 3 there were a total of 2,336 confirmed cases of new pneumonia in Iran, including 77 deaths, with a mortality rate of about 3.29% .

As confirmed cases continue to increase, Iran's epidemic prevention work is also in full swing. Recently, a number of cities in Iran opened dedicated to the treatment of new coronavirus infection of infectious diseases hospital. In the central Iranian city of Yazd, the government has promised to build a 1,000 sq m hospital within days. In the holy city of Qom, where the outbreak first broke out, the Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution also opened a field hospital for new cases of pneumonia.

In less than two weeks since the first confirmed cases were announced, Iran has become the country with the second highest number of confirmed cases outside China, after South Korea.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Field Hospital under construction

Iran's version of Mount Vulcan begins construction

The central Iranian city of Yazd is focusing on building a hospital to treat people infected with the new coronavirus, the Tasnim News Agency reported on March 2. Construction of the hospital has been under way since March 1 and will be completed later this week if all goes according to plan, said Mahmud ibn Muhammad Desguin, deputy minister of infrastructure and transport in Yazd, it will then be delivered to medical facilities to begin operations.

The hospital covers an area of 1,000 square meters and has emergency wards, rest areas for medical staff and a concentration of biomedical waste, Tasnim News Agency reported.

According to Russian satellite news agency, the construction of the hospital is reminiscent of the "Vulcan Mountain" and "Thor Mountain" hospitals built in Wuhan, China, in just one week last month.

Revolutionary Guard ground forces on alert

In Qom, the holy city of the worst affected, Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution has opened a new field hospital for new coronavirus infections. Iran Press, Iran's semi official media, reported that the field hospital is located in Qom's industrial zone and has 180 beds. It comprises an emergency room, a High Level Clinic, a radiology department, an inpatient department and a pharmacy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Doctors at the field hospital

Muhammad, commander of the Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution Ground Forces, said his unit had set up a "biological operations base" to combat the new pneumonia outbreak, the Tasnim News Agency reported, biology and virology experts from the Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution have also been deployed to areas of Iran that have been particularly affected by the virus.

He added that all modern armed military units at 10 Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution bases were on alert.

In the meantime, the Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution's medical team has prepared designated hospitals, mobile hospitals and rapid response medical teams to assist the Iranian Ministry of Health.

The army stopped recruiting

In addition, Iran also began to attach importance to the military epidemic prevention work. The Iranian armed forces have postponed mandatory military recruitment for the coming weeks.

Brigadier General Hassan, a spokesman for the Iranian armed forces'new coronavirus fighting team, announced on March 2 that he had decided to postpone enlistment for at least two months, according to Radio Farda, an Iranian news website with U.S. backing.

Brigadier General Behzad Moazeni, head of the Medical Department of Iran's regular army ground forces, told the Iranian labor news agency (ILNA) in an interview on March 1 that the army is taking all appropriate measures to prevent the spread of coronavirus in the army. Moazeni said army training sessions and mass prayer sessions had been cancelled.

So far, no new cases of coronavirus infection have been found among Iranian army units, according to Moazeni.
